<br>
-------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
I took the time to type this up for somewhere else, so why not put it here also...<br>
<br>
batch file are REALLY easy to make. You can make them without any extra tools or programs. Just follow a few steps.<br>
<br>
First of all, for those who don't know, a batch file is a dos Macro runner. You can have it run pre-entered dos commands really easily...<br>
<br>
-Create a new text file with a convenient and simple name<br>
<br>
-Edit that file to contain the dos commands to want the bat file to do, example: (one on each line)<br>
c:<br>
cd windows<br>
cd desktop<br>
<br>
(yea, I know you could do all that with c:/ windows/desktop...)<br>
A bat file such as that one will change the directory to c:/ windows/desktop/ and is useful for quickly changing to deep or long named directories quickly. <br>
<br>
-After you are done wrinting in commands, save the file, rename it to a *.bat file, and put it into the directory you want to run it from. <br>
<br>
-You can run the program from windows or dos, and it will run the dos commands you entered in the text in dos, and it will act like you had just typed them in.<br>
<br>
-This is why you want it named a simple name: To run it in dos, just type the name of the file. I named my desktop bat file 'desktop', so I type that in and it will change the directory.<br>
If the file is in a different directory, just type out the whole filename. (NOTE: you must use it's dos name, which may be different)<br>
I just typed, c:/desktop and it sent me to c:/windows/desktop/<br>
<br>
Neat huh?<br>
